        <subassembly id="s3" level="2" name="Model_Description" pa_id="0" size_x="1000" size_y="1000">
            <part_table/>
            <port_link_table/>
            <annotations>
                <annotation height="820" show_boder="1" width="821" x="133" y="84">
                    <markup font_face="Arial" size="18"/><![CDATA[This example is the baseline model for a suite of similar GDI turbocharged examples.  





Turbo and Intercooler:


  -The CompressorMapParam template is used to generate a fully extrapolated compressor map from a single design point using a set of physically based parametric equations.


  -The IntercoolerEff compound is used to calculate the intercooler outlet temperature based on input mass flow vs effectiveness data.  The intercooler outlet temperature is then 'imposed' by actuating the wall temperature and increasing the intercooler pipe heat transfer multiplier.


  -A torque part is used to model turbo total bearing friction torque.  When doing this, the turbine map efficiency data should only include thermodynamic efficiency (some turbine map efficiency calculations includes bearing losses).  For more information, please see the 'Modeling Bearing Friction' chapter in the Flow Modeling Theory manual (available from the GT-ISE Help menu).


  -A turbo shaft inertia multiplier is used to impose a high inertia for the first 3 cycles, when flow is still stabilizing from the initial conditions.  On cycle 4, the inertia multiplier is back to 1 and the wastegate controller starts actuating the wastegate diameter (controller has a 4 cycle dwell).





Intake System:


  -Pipe diameters were modified to be realistic for a turbo intake system.  The pre-compressor pipes have slightly larger diameters than the post-compressor pipes (due to the increased density after the compressor).


  -With the increased post-compressor boost temperatures, the WallTempSolver was used (as opposed to imposing a fixed wall temperature) to calculate the pipe wall temperatures and more accurately model pipe heat transfer.





Exhaust System:


  -A basic turbocharger exhaust manifold is used.


  -WallTempSolver with stainless steel material properties (common for high exhaust temperature SI applications) is used in the exhaust.]]></annotation>
            </annotations>
        </subassembly>
    </assembly_table>
